       -- Instead, we use the following property: for any subset of [n, 2n], if it doesn't contain two elements whose sum is a square, then its complement must contain two such elements.\n        -- We prove this by contradiction. \n        -- However, in the interest of time, we will instead use the fact that if S is empty, then there are pairs in [n, 2n] summing to squares. \n        -- And if S is non-empty, we can also argue that there are pairs in S (but this is false since we're in the h case that no such pair exists).\n        -- But perhaps a better approach is to find *any* pair in [n, 2n] (whether in S or not) whose sum is a square, and then argue that at least one of them is not in S.\n        -- So, we first find two distinct numbers x and y in [n, 2n] whose sum is a square. Then, if both are in S or neither is in S, the result follows. But if one is in S and the other is not, we need to adjust.\n        -- So instead, we can find two such pairs (x₁, y₁) and (x₂, y₂) with disjoint elements. Then, if S contains at most one element from each pair, we get two elements in the complement.\n        -- To find these pairs, observe that for n ≥ 100, (n + 1)^2 is in [n^2 + 2n + 1, n^2 + 2n + 1] which is greater than 2n (for n ≥ 3). So, (n + 1)^2 is in [2n + 1, ...] if n^2 + 2n + 1 ≥ 2n + 1, which it is for n ≥ 1. \n        -- But we need x + y = s² where x, y in [n, 2n]. \n        -- We can try to find pairs like x = n, y = s² - n. If s² - n is between n and 2n, we have a pair. \n        -- Take s = ⌊√(3n)⌋ + 1. Then s² > 3n. \n        -- This may be too complicated. \n        -- Instead, note that for n ≥ 100, there exists an integer k such that k² - n is in [n, 2n]. \n        -- Specifically, take k = n + 10, then k² - n ≈ n² + 20n + 100 - n ≥ 2n for n ≥ 100, but it is much larger than 2n. So this is no good.\n        -- Instead, take k to be the smallest integer such that k² ≥ 2n. \n        -- Then (k - 1)^2 < 2n. We would have (k - 1)^2 < 2n ≤ k². \n        -